Parser

Enum Function

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<Function>
      • Parser.Function
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<Function>

    public enum Function
extends java.lang.Enum<Function>
    Enumeration that binds functions to their function name. Functions must implement a calculate method, which takes one or more (arg, varargs) Object parameters of type Number, Boolean, Reference or Range and returns the result of the calculation as Number.
    Author:
    Jan-Willem Gmelig Meyling

    • Enum Constant Detail

      • ADD

        public static final Function ADD
        The ADD-function adds the values of the arguments, and returns the result in the type of the first argument. For example: if the first argument is an instance of Integer and the second and third arguments are instances of Double, these arguments are rounded to the closest Integer and added to the result of type Integer.

        When the input doesn't make any sense (adding a String or Boolean) a IllegalArgumentException is thrown.
        Authors:
        • Jan-Willem Gmelig Meyling

      • SUBTRACT

        public static final Function SUBTRACT
        The SUBTRACT-function subtracts the values of the arguments from the first argument, and returns the result in the type of the first argument. For example: if the first argument is an instance of Integer and the second and third arguments are instances of Double, these arguments are rounded to the closest Integer.

        When the input doesn't make any sense (adding a String or Boolean) a IllegalArgumentException is thrown.
        Authors:
        • Jan-Willem Gmelig Meyling

For example: if the first argument is an instance of Integer and the second and third arguments are instances of Double, these arguments are rounded to the closest Integer.

        public static final Function POWER
        The POWER-function takes two arguments, and returns the first argument to the power of the second argument, in the type of the first argument. For example: if the first argument is an instance of Integer and the second argument is an instances of Double, this argument rounded to the closest Integer for the calculation.

        When the input doesn't make any sense (adding a String or Boolean) a IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

      • intValueOf

        public static int intValueOf(java.lang.Object obj)
        Get the integer value of an object. Values of the type Double will be rounded to the closest integer and Booleans will be converted to their integer value: 1 for true and 0 for false. Values of the type String will always be converted to 0.
        Parameters:
        obj - Object to convert
        Returns:
        integer value to calculate with

      • doubleValueOf

        public static double doubleValueOf(java.lang.Object obj)
        Get the double value of an object. Values of the type Boolean will be converted to their integer value: 1 for true and 0 for false. Values of the type String will always be converted to 0.
        Parameters:
        obj - Object to convert
        Returns:
        double value to calculate with

      • booleanValueOf

        public static boolean booleanValueOf(java.lang.Object obj)
        Logic operations will use the boolean type for calculations. Arguments with other types will be converted to a boolean value. Integer and Double-values with a value greater or equal to 1 will be parsed as true, values less than 1 will be parsed as false. Values of the type String with a length greater than 1 will be parsed as true, else false.
        Parameters:
        obj - Object to convert
        Returns:
        boolean value to calculate with
